SIMPLE: renegade
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Renegade
<hw>Ren"e*gade</hw> <pr>(r?n"?-g?d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp.
<ets>renegado</ets>, LL. <ets>renegatus</ets>, fr. <ets>renegare</ets>
to deny; L. pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>negare</ets> to deny. See
<er>Negation</er>, <ets>and cf</ets>. <er>Runagate</er>.]</ety> <def>One
faithless to principle or party.</def> Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>An apostate from Christianity or from any form of religious
faith.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>James justly regarded these <qex>renegades</qex> as the most
serviceable tools that he could employ.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>One who deserts from a military or naval post; a
deserter.</def> <au>Arbuthnot.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A common vagabond;
a worthless or wicked fellow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Renegado</ent>⟦br⟧
